{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621166"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16679"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16679"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.52,0,0.1,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66296"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9370"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51745"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2419"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5401"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22180"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66296"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe occurrence and spread of infectious diseases in populations can be understood through a conceptual framework that describes the relationship between three essential elements.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the three components of the epidemiological triad?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Disease, transmission, and prevention","Host, agent, and environment","Pathogen, vector, and climate","Risk, exposure, and outcome","Susceptibility, virulence, and contact"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe epidemiological triad is a fundamental model in public health that consists of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehost, agent, and environment\u003C/strong\u003E. Each component plays a crucial role:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHost: The organism capable of being infected (e.g., humans), with factors like immunity status, age, and genetics affecting susceptibility\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAgent: The pathogen or factor that causes disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEnvironment: The external conditions that influence disease transmission and spread\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent misconceptions about the triad:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisease, transmission, and prevention\u003C/strong\u003E describe outcomes and interventions rather than the interacting components that cause disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPathogen, vector, and climate\u003C/strong\u003E are too specific and represent only subsets of the broader categories\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk, exposure, and outcome\u003C/strong\u003E describe the sequence of disease development rather than the essential interacting elements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESusceptibility, virulence, and contact\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristics of the main components rather than the primary elements themselves\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDisease prevention strategies target one or more components of this triad - strengthening host immunity through vaccination, controlling disease agents through antimicrobials, or modifying environmental conditions to prevent transmission.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The epidemiological triad consists of three key components: host, agent, and environment.","Disease occurs when there is an interaction between a susceptible host, a disease-causing agent, and environmental conditions that allow transmission.","Understanding the epidemiological triad is fundamental for disease prevention and control strategies."],"references":["John TJ, Kompithra RZ. Eco-epidemiology triad to explain infectious diseases. Indian J Med Res. 2023 Aug;158(2):107-112. doi: 10.4103/ijmr.ijmr_3031_21. PMID: 37675687; PMCID: PMC10645024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51745"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16679"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51745"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T18:32:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T22:48:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9370"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66296"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,